Legal tools were stretched to fit this posture. The administration leaned on the Alien Enemies Act, an eighteenth\uc0\u8209 century wartime statute, to deport Venezuelan migrants, often on the basis of tattoos or thin gang allegations. Visas and legal status for South Sudanese nationals and CBP One parolees were revoked en masse, turning lawful presence into a privilege that could be withdrawn by policy memo. Social Security numbers for some immigrants with temporary status were canceled, pushing them out of the workforce and toward \'93self\u8209 deportation\'94 without formal hearings. Rights on paper became fragile in practice.\
