The courts themselves occupied an uneasy middle ground between resistance and accommodation. On one track, the Supreme Court issued emergency orders that allowed deportations under the Alien Enemies Act to proceed, narrowing collective legal remedies and pushing challenges into more executive\uc0\u8209 friendly venues. In another case, the Court stayed and later overturned lower\u8209 court rulings that would have required rehiring sixteen thousand purged federal probationary workers, enabling the administration\'92s mass dismissals to stand and weakening the independence of the civil service. Deference to executive claims carried real institutional cost.\
