Transparency about power and influence eroded in parallel. The White House\'92s refusal to release its claimed list of trade\uc0\u8209 partner countries, the scaling back of FARA enforcement, and sanctions on cooperation with the International Criminal Court all reduced the flow of information about foreign influence and war\u8209 crimes investigations. Press access was conditioned on adopting executive rebranding of geographic terms, and only a court order restored the Associated Press\'92s place in the briefing room. Corporations, wary of retaliation, stayed quiet about tariffs that harmed their own interests. In this environment, data and algorithms were used not to illuminate public choices but to target individuals for enforcement and to justify policies whose full contours the public could not see.\
